{
  "title": "Unit Testing Stream Processing with FastAPI in Python 3.12+",
  "summary": "This guide explains how to write effective unit tests for stream processing applications built using FastAPI and Python 3.12+, emphasizing the utilization of asynchronous testing features provided by Python 3.12.",

  "key_points": [
    "Leverage FastAPI's built-in test client for testing endpoints",
    "Use FastAPI's asynchronous context manager to write tests in an async-friendly manner",
    "Employ FastAPI's test utilities, such as `FastAPI.test_client` and `override_strategies`, for test setup and teardown",
    "Write unit tests for stream processing endpoints using FastAPI's test client in an async-coroutine context",
    "Mock dependencies or external services when necessary to isolate the stream processing logic in your tests"
  ],

  "code_examples": [
    {
      "language": "python",
      "code": "async def test_streaming_endpoint():\n    client = FastAPI.test_client()\n    response = await client.get('/stream')\n    assert response.status_code == 200"
    },
    {
      "language": "python",
      "code": "async def test_streaming_endpoint_with_mocks():\n    from unittest.mock import patch\n    @patch('your_module.some_dependency')\n    async def test_with_mocked_dep(mocked_dep):\n        # Your test code using the mocked dependency"
    }
  ],

  "version_notes": [
    "These examples are designed for Python 3.12+ and FastAPI 0.74.0 or later",
    "Ensure your environment is set up to use Python 3.12 when running tests"
  ],

  "caveats": [
    "While FastAPI provides robust testing features, it's important to remember that unit testing stream processing can be complex due to the nature of asynchronous code and data streams",
    "Consider using tools like Pytest-AsyncIO for more advanced asynchronous test support"
  ]
}
